Helios was raining down his muddy boots - my brother that in his glasses I see eyes becoming pellets ready to fly flowers from within. The other sun of my day,  the bright father of our kind,  warmed our backs. The silence brought me to your door, the marble daughters of the courtyard greeted me, the greenhouse was shouting at me to break in, to hide briefly from the cemetery next to your garden. I found letters in your office that were not sent. Was it any of them for me? Low ceilings, wings would rust. You ripped them off to wrap Shakespeare's collection beside your unwrinkled bed. I confess, like a wounded Romeo - I peel the leaves at the bottom of your garden lake. They'll stay there longer than me to guard you. The flowers came out. Smile, warm. His. I am to him what you are to me. A candle made of the melted moon. üçÅ@helias_doulis

Today is the birthday of the man that gave me a better and deeper understanding of who I am. @helias_doulis let me dive into Parabyss, the utopia of his mind, he helped me blossom despite my solitude and guided me so I'd never stop at what it seems a dead end. This little ode to my prince will always have a starting and ending point with the movie we made, 'The Nest', cos for me that is the most vivid memory of the years on his side, the one that I have from when I opened my wounded wings for the first time and maybe the last. When Narcissus died the pool of his pleasure changed from a cup of sweet waters into a cup of salt tears, and the Oreads came weeping through the woodland that they might sing to the pool and give it comfort. / And when they saw that the pool had changed from a cup of sweet waters into a cup of salt tears, they loosened the green tresses of their hair and cried to the pool and said, 'We do not wonder that you should mourn in this manner for Narcissus, so beautiful was he.' / 'But was Narcissus beautiful?' said the pool. / 'Who should know that better than you?' answered the Oreads. 'Us did he ever pass by, but you he sought for, and would lie on your banks and look down at you, and in the mirror of your waters he would mirror his own beauty.' / And the pool answered, 'But I loved Narcissus because, as he lay on my banks and looked down at me, in the mirror of his eyes I saw ever my own beauty mirrored.'
The Disciple by Oscar Wilde

Ephedrismos (·ºêœÜŒµŒ¥œÅŒπœÉŒºœåœÇ; "to be carried in someone's back") was an ancient greek game for two players of the same sex which according to the evidence of monuments became popular in the 5th century BC till the the death of Alexander the Great (323 BC) and the emergence of the Roman Empire.
This type of ‚Äúpiggyback‚Äù game was mostly played by first placing a stone on the ground and then throwing a pebble or a ball at the set stone, in an attempt to knock it over. The player who was unable to overturn the stone had to carry the winner on his or her back, while the winner covered his or her eyes. This part of the game continued until the loser was able to touch the overturned stone.
Although ephedrismos groups depict a scene of everyday life, they also had an additional, symbolic meaning. The winner in this game, who is carried on the loser‚Äôs back, was seen by the ancients as symbolizing Eros or Aphrodite. Therefore, the representation of a young girl playing ephedrismos could be interpreted as a sign that she will find love or/even get married.
The erotic and epithalamic associations of the game of ephedrismos have many variations and depictions. It was always though played between youths of the same sex because of the physical proximity it creates.The personification of Eros or Aphrodite is the one you have to 'carry on your back' and now you're under his/her commands.

There are numerous myths that ancient Greeks invented in order to explain the important strategic position of Thira and the whole island complex of Cyclades during the Bronze Age and the geological changes that took place in Mediterranean.
The most fascinating myth about the natural disaster in Thira (and the world‚Äôs geomorphology in general), is the one of Helios (Sun) and his chariot, which he drove across the sky each day:

In the myth, Helios' son, the demigod Phaethon, travelled to the East to meet his father for the first time and envied his power. He, then, asked him to pull his chariot just for one day, as passionately as Hippolytus would ask. However, Phaethon was still young, inexperienced and weak and Helios hesitated and tried to talk him out, but in the end he allowed his son to take over the reins of the horses.
Once the horses felt that their master was no longer dominating, they went out of control and started jumping constantly up and down. The beautiful face of Phaethon was turned into a mask of fear like Icarus when his wings started to melt. Whenever the chariot came very close to the sun, the earth and rivers dried out. Whenever the chariot was distant, the earth was covered in snow and ice.
God Zeus, the master of the gods, wanted to save the Earth. So he hurled his thunderbolt at the chariot, turning this way the horses into stone, and throwed the flaming body of the dead Phaethon into a river.
In ‚ÄúThe Tears of Phaethon's Sisters‚Äù, Cavafy wrote on this tragic theme of young men‚Äôs failure at the hands of hubris:
'Within our humble homes
let we might live frugal and despicable;
let us pour the cravings out of the heart.
let all this inclination to the sky to cease.'
But can we? üì∑@stephen_tirely

Openly gay Thanos Murray-Velloudios (1895-1992) was a fearless Greek aviator (in 1920 he landed near Bursa in Asia Minor where he put up the Greek flag), a folklore expert and promoter of Hellenism, supporter of Angelos Sikelianos and Eva Palmer during the Delphi Festivities for the rebirth of Ancient Theatre, friend of Yannis Tsarouchi's, actor, photographer and the first Greek dadaist painter.
